### Reified Type Parameters in Kotlin

Reified type parameters allow accessing the actual type at runtime inside inline functions. Normally, generic types are erased at runtime (type erasure).

---

### Type Erasure Problem

```kotlin
// This does NOT compile
fun <T> isString(value: Any): Boolean {
    // return value is T  // Error: Cannot check instance of erased type
}
```

---

### Reified Solution

```kotlin
inline fun <reified T> isType(value: Any): Boolean {
    return value is T  // Works with reified
}

fun main() {
    println(isType<String>("Hello"))  // true
    println(isType<Int>("Hello"))     // false
}
```

---

### Requirements for Reified

| Requirement | Description |
|-------------|-------------|
| `inline` | Function must be marked `inline` |
| `reified` | Type parameter must be `reified` |
| No `crossinline`/`noinline` | Not supported with reified (use separate params) |
| JVM only | Works on JVM (not Kotlin/Native in all cases) |

---

### Common Use Cases

#### Type Checking
```kotlin
inline fun <reified T> checkType(value: Any): String {
    return when (value) {
        is T -> "Matches ${T::class.simpleName}"
        else -> "Does not match"
    }
}
```

#### Accessing Class
```kotlin
inline fun <reified T> classInfo() {
    println("Type: ${T::class.qualifiedName}")
    println("Simple: ${T::class.simpleName}")
    println("Is abstract: ${T::class.isAbstract}")
}
```

---

### Creating Instances via Reified

```kotlin
inline fun <reified T> createInstance(): T? {
    return try {
        T::class.constructors.first().call()
    } catch (e: Exception) {
        null
    }
}
```

---

### Reified with JSON Parsing

```kotlin
inline fun <reified T> parseJson(json: String): T {
    return Json.decodeFromString<T>(json)
}

// Usage
val user = parseJson<User>("{"name":"Alice"}")
```

---

### Limitations

Reified types cannot be used:
- In non-inline functions
- In property types (only function type parameters)
- In classes (only functions)

> **Key Point:** Reified type parameters solve the type erasure problem by inlining the actual type at the call site. Required for `is T`, `as T`, and `T::class` in generic functions.

codeExample:
inline fun <reified T> List<*>.filterByType(): List<T> {
    return this.filterIsInstance<T>()
}

fun main() {
    val mixed = listOf(1, "Hello", 2, "World", 3.14)

    val strings: List<String> = mixed.filterByType()
    val ints: List<Int> = mixed.filterByType()

    println("Strings: $strings")  // [Hello, World]
    println("Ints: $ints")        // [1, 2]

    inline fun <reified T> className() = T::class.simpleName
    println(className<String>())  // String
    println(className<Int>())     // Int
}
